{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos257.erdos_257 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos257.erdos_257.","id":"vf_52707b89fe55d4db","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #257: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $A\\subseteq \\mathbb{N}$ be an infinite set. Is\\[\\sum_{n\\in A}\\frac{1}{2^n-1}\\]irrational? Current best: There is nothing special about $2$ here, and this sum is likely irrational with $2$ replaced by any integer $t\\geq 2$. This was disproved by Kova\\v{c} and Tao \\cite{KoTa24}, and in the comments Kova\\v{c} has sketched a proof that there exists some choice of $t_n$ with $1\\leq t_n\\leq 6$ such that this sum is rational. Prize: no. Tags: irrationality.","id":"vf_c012e9b8b1780dcd","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[{"accepted":false,"banked":true,"claim":"The Lean 4 theorem `Erdos257.erdos_257.variants.tsum_top_eq` is proven and kernel-verified (axioms: propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound; no sorryAx): the Lambert-series identity ∑_{n≥1} 1/(2^n - 1) = ∑_{n≥1} d(n)/2^n, where d(n) is the number of divisors of n. Closes a previously-open, UNCLAIMED `sorry` (category: textbook) in google-deepmind/formal-conjectures Erdős Problem 257.","claimed_status":"","classification":"importable_attempt","id":"vat_d1b6599eaf5c9e76","kind":"theorem","lifecycle":"banked","location":"current_commit","mathematical_scope":"variant","method_channel":"","method_families":["lambert_series","divisor_counting","infinite_sums","lean_kernel"],"named_obstructions":["original_set_theoretic_statement"],"related_problems":[],"remaining_obligations":["The source proves the displayed Lambert-series variant, not the full original Erdős 257 statement."],"source_ref":"frontier.json#vat_d1b6599eaf5c9e76","trust":"signed"},{"accepted":false,"claim":"Pinned Formal Conjectures activity classification; integration activity does not establish mathemat